My Tamagotchi application

1\. Purpose

So we were asked to create a Tamagotchi application, where our/ my pet will be able to perform certain tasks. I went ahead and chose a pet that’s a rabbit because I think they are the cutest pets that were ever created. The name of my pet is Duke. The reason why I am making this app is because I want to give young kids from the ages of 5 to 10 years old a chance to have fun, but also at the same time, I want them to learn how to be responsible for their own. How they will learn this responsibility is that, since my rabbit Duke will have to bath, sleep, and play, and if none of these tasks are performed, Duke will not be a very happy rabbit, whereas if they perform all these tasks, Duke will be a very happy rabbit.

2\. Design Considerations

Here I will speak about the name of my application. The name of my application is called, “ Dukes Application”. I chose this name because it is not a very common name among pets. The picture that I will be showing below, will be my home screen.

More information:

All the buttons that the user will be clicking will be linked to a progress bar that I will later have to code in the project. What this progress bar does is that it measures if the rabbit has done all the activities and if it has, the progress bar will then be on 100, but if the rabbit hasn’t completed at least 1 of these activities, then the progress bar will decrease to a certain number below 100.

What about the buttons:

The very first button that the user will click, is the “ Play Duke” button, which will take you to the second page, where you will complete all the activities. The user will be able to go to the next page because I have created a code that will link the two pages.

When the user clicks the “ Eat Food” button on the second screen, the picture will first change to the rabbit eating, this is the page where the rabbit will eat, and the hungriness of the rabbit will be measured on the progress bar, and when the rabbit has eaten, it will be full, meaning that it will be on 100%.

When the user clicks the “ Have Fun” button on the second page, this is the page where the rabbit will play and have fun, it will also be monitored by a progress bar, and also when the rabbit has played, the progress bar will be 100.

And lastly, for the second page, when the user clicks on the “Rest” button, the picture will change to a rabbit resting, or sleeping, this will happen when the user has completed all the activities that the rabbit must perform. Once the user is done with every activity on this page, the user will be able to go back to the home page.

General Design:

The design of my application is user-friendly to the users, which will be kids because I did not use inappropriate pictures and also because most of my texts are in light colors.

Intuitive Design

Yes, my design is easy to follow, because I only have 2 pages that the user will interact with and also because the buttons are basically self-explanatory.

Content Prioritization:

Yes, I only included the necessary information that needs to be used, meaning that, the 3 buttons that the user will interact with, and the picture of my pet. I also followed the instructions on what kind of activities the pet must do.

Legible Text Content:

As you can see, the text on both my buttons is readable, because I used big fonts, and also the color of my buttons is not too bright, which will cause the user not to read clearly.

Hand Position Controls:

On the first page, there is only 1 bug button that the user will click, then on the second page, there are 3 buttons that are close to each other and are not hard to see. This will also help the user easily click any button they want to click.

Images:

The reason why I chose these images of the rabbit, is because they were easier to find, and also I did not want a real-life image, I wanted something that would be close to cartoons since this app is basically for young kids.
